  "texts": [
    "For the present study, it is beyond scope to present our full axiomatic theory L of cognitive likelihood that is subsumed by IDCEC, in which Kolmogorov's axioms do not hold.",
    "E.g., where p yields the probability of an event/proposition φ, Kolmogorov's second axiom says that if φ is a theorem in a standard, elementary extensional logic (such as the propositional calculus), p(φ)=1.",
    "However, theorems in such a logic are not at all guaranteed to have a likelihood value of 5, since an infinite number of such theorems are not familiar to human beings and hence cannot be believed.",
    "In addition, theorems of L are often completely without corresponding analogs in the probability calculus.",
    "E.g., \"if ℓ(φ) = 5, ℓ(¬φ) = 0\" is a theorem in L that has no analog in the probability calculus."
  ],
  "correct_citations": []
}